29 SECTION 5. Arkansas Code § 17-28-302 is repealed.
30 17-28-302. Electrical contractor license.
31 (a) Any person, member, or employee of a firm, partnership, or
32 corporation desiring to engage in the business of electrical contractor may
33 apply for and be issued a license upon satisfying the Board of Electrical
34 Examiners of the State of Arkansas that he or she or it is either a master
35 electrician or employs a master electrician as its superintendent or manager
36 and shall pay a license fee in the amount of one hundred dollars ($100) per
5 04-07-2025 15:06:51 LGL199
As Engrossed: S4/7/25 SB627
1 year.
2 (b) Any electrical contractor having met the requirements of this
3 chapter may work in any municipality in the state without further
4 examinations after first showing evidence of state license as described in
5 this chapter and paying such fees as required by the municipality in which
6 the work is to be performed.
7
8 SECTION 6. Arkansas Code § 17-28-308 is amended to read as follows:
9 17-28-308. Electrical apprentices.
10 (a) Upon proper application and payment of the fee, the Board of
11 Electrical Examiners of the State of Arkansas shall register as an electrical
12 apprentice and issue a certificate of registration to any person who
13 furnishes satisfactory proof that the applicant is enrolled in a school or
14 training course for electrical apprentices certified by the United States
15 Office of Apprenticeship.
16 (b) The board shall take such actions as are reasonably necessary or
17 appropriate to supervise and enforce apprenticeship supervision ratios
18 established by the board by rule.
19 (c) Notwithstanding the provisions of subsection (a) of this section,
20 an apprentice who has successfully completed a certified school or training
21 program and has been released for testing may continue to renew his or her
22 apprentice registration card, if otherwise qualified, without enrolling in a
23 school or training program shall test within one (1) year of release by the
24 Office of Skills Development.
25 (d) Application for an initial certificate of registration and renewal
26 of an electrical apprentice shall be the responsibility of the school or
27 training course for electrical apprentices certified by the United States
28 Office of Apprenticeship in which the electrical apprentice is enrolled.
29 (e) The school or training course for electrical apprentices certified
30 by the United States Office of Apprenticeship in which the electrical
31 apprentice is enrolled shall be responsible for documenting on-the-job
32 training hours of apprentice electricians and submitting completion of hours
33 to the board when releasing an apprentice electrician for testing.
34
35 SECTION 7. Arkansas Code § 17-28-309 is amended to read as follows:
36 17-28-309. Penalties.
6 04-07-2025 15:06:51 LGL199
As Engrossed: S4/7/25 SB627
1 (a) The Director of the Division of Occupational and Professional
2 Licensing Boards and Commissions Secretary of the Department of Labor and
3 Licensing or his or her designee is authorized to petition any court of
4 competent jurisdiction to enjoin or restrain any person who performs
5 electrical work without a license or who otherwise violates the provisions of
6 this chapter.
7 (b)(1) A civil penalty may be assessed against any person, firm, or
8 corporation by the Division of Occupational and Professional Licensing Boards
9 and Commissions Department of Labor and Licensing and subject to appeal and
10 hearing before the Board of Electrical Examiners of the State of Arkansas
11 according to the Arkansas Administrative Procedure Act, § 25-15-201 et seq.,
12 if it is determined that a person, firm, or corporation has violated any:
13 (A) Provision of this chapter;
14 (B) Provision of the Arkansas Electrical Code Authority
15 Act, § 20-31-101 et seq.;
16 (C) Rule or order issued or promulgated by the board; or
17 (D) Condition of a license, certificate, or registration
18 issued by the board.; or
19 (E) Licensure eligibility concerning criminal records
20 under § 17-3-102.
21 (2) For each violation, the penalty shall not exceed the
22 following: one thousand dollars ($1,000) per day.
23 (A) Two hundred fifty dollars ($250) for a first offense;
24 (B) Seven hundred fifty dollars ($750) for a second
25 offense; or
26 (C) One thousand dollars ($1,000) for a third offense.
27 (3) Each day of a continuing violation is a separate violation
28 for purposes of penalty assessment.
29 (4)(A) Assessment of a civil penalty by the board shall be made
30 no later than two (2) years after the date of the occurrence of the
31 violation.
32 (B) No civil penalty may be assessed until the person
33 charged with the violation has been given the opportunity for a hearing on
34 the violation.
35 (5) If any person, firm, or corporation against whom a civil
36 penalty has been imposed fails to pay the penalty within sixty (60) days of
7 04-07-2025 15:06:51 LGL199
As Engrossed: S4/7/25 SB627
1 the board’s decision, the director secretary or his or her designee may file
2 an action in a court of competent jurisdiction to collect the civil penalty
3 without paying costs or giving bond for costs.
4 (6) Any penalties collected under this section shall be
5 deposited as special revenues into the State Treasury to the credit of the
6 Department of Labor and Licensing Special Fund, there to be used by the
7 Department of Labor and Licensing in carrying out the functions, powers, and
8 duties of this chapter.
